WEBVTT

00:02.103 --> 00:04.238
* Ah ah, ah ah, ah-ah-ah-ah

00:04.272 --> 00:05.739
* Ah ah, ah ah, ah-ah

00:05.773 --> 00:07.875
Oh, careful.
[ Laughs ]

00:07.908 --> 00:10.411
You was almost about
to have to buy me dinner.

00:10.444 --> 00:13.114
There we go.

00:13.147 --> 00:15.116
Interviewer: Um, how long have
you been with the FBI?

00:15.149 --> 00:16.417
Three whole months.

00:16.450 --> 00:18.419
In case y'all didn't notice,
I'm Black.

00:18.452 --> 00:21.189
So all this harsh light
y'all got me under,

00:21.222 --> 00:22.956
it's gonna be a problem.

00:22.990 --> 00:25.193
Y'all got a diffuser or
something you can put on this?

00:25.226 --> 00:27.027
If not, you can dial down
the key light

00:27.061 --> 00:29.029
and bring it
a little closer.

00:29.063 --> 00:30.731
'Cause it's either that
or I'm gonna have to wipe

00:30.764 --> 00:32.600
some Vaseline
[chuckling] on the lens.

00:32.633 --> 00:33.934
Wow, you really know
your stuff.

00:33.967 --> 00:36.237
I used to be a high school
guidance counselor.

00:36.270 --> 00:38.439
So I had my share
of substitute teaching

00:38.472 --> 00:41.109
the media arts department.

00:41.142 --> 00:42.810
How about I just help
y'all out?

00:42.843 --> 00:46.280
Uh, actually, that's not kosher
with the union...

00:46.314 --> 00:47.548
So, you're a rookie?

00:47.581 --> 00:49.483
Probationary agent.

00:49.517 --> 00:51.752
But even though
I'm relatively new to it,

00:51.785 --> 00:53.587
I've seen some crazy things.

00:53.621 --> 00:55.389
Like the Laughlin
investigation?

00:55.423 --> 00:57.057
[ Dramatic music plays ]

00:57.091 --> 00:59.593
Yeah.

00:59.627 --> 01:00.794
That one shook me.

01:00.828 --> 01:06.134
**

01:06.167 --> 01:11.472
**

01:12.506 --> 01:13.807
Good morning.

01:13.841 --> 01:16.210
Interviewer:
Good to see you again.
Thanks for doing this.

01:16.244 --> 01:17.777
You ready to just
jump right in?

01:17.811 --> 01:19.012
Let's do it.

01:19.045 --> 01:20.581
Tell me about the day you found
the body in the hills.

01:20.614 --> 01:23.451
It was the morning I started
filming my reality show --

01:23.484 --> 01:24.952
Wait.
You have a reality show?

01:24.985 --> 01:26.654
Oh, when you got a money-maker
like this

01:26.687 --> 01:28.256
and a life like mine,

01:28.289 --> 01:30.458
it demands documentation.

01:30.491 --> 01:32.793
I'm shooting
the pilot episode myself.

01:32.826 --> 01:34.328
Wow.
And what's it called?

01:34.362 --> 01:36.664
[ Rock music plays ]

01:36.697 --> 01:38.966
[ Siren wailing ]

01:38.999 --> 01:40.234
[ Cell door clangs ]

01:40.268 --> 01:42.470
Dispatch: 7-Adam-9,
Nichols Canyon,

01:42.503 --> 01:45.273
report of a mudslide
blocking the road.

01:45.306 --> 01:47.775
There was a heavy rain
last night.

01:47.808 --> 01:50.978
So, like, almost an inch.

01:51.011 --> 01:53.814
When water falls
from the sky here,

01:53.847 --> 01:59.019
the city of angels becomes
a city of demons.

01:59.051 --> 02:01.889
But not today.

02:01.922 --> 02:04.725
Not on "Smitty's Streets."

02:04.758 --> 02:06.894
Holy [bleep]

02:06.926 --> 02:09.896
[ Dramatic music plays ]

02:09.930 --> 02:16.837
**

02:16.870 --> 02:19.940
The name of the victim
was Dante Smith.

02:19.973 --> 02:21.442
He was a missing persons.

02:21.475 --> 02:24.812
Disappeared about eight months
before his body was found.

02:24.845 --> 02:26.680
But the mystery was, I mean,
he'd only been dead

02:26.714 --> 02:29.183
for less than 24 hours.

02:29.216 --> 02:31.619
We didn't know where he'd been
for all that time.

02:31.652 --> 02:32.886
Interviewer:
What did you know about him?

02:32.920 --> 02:35.723
The poor boy came to L.A.
with a dollar and a dream,

02:35.756 --> 02:37.391
hoping to become an actor.

02:37.425 --> 02:39.293
But [chuckles]
let's just say,

02:39.327 --> 02:41.028
he wasn't very realistic
about his talents.

02:41.061 --> 02:42.530
Whoa, whoa, whoa.
Hey, hey, hey.
And I --

02:42.563 --> 02:44.598
What?
That's mean.
You don't have to say that.

02:44.632 --> 02:48.202
What?
You know he w--
h-he wasn't that good.

02:48.236 --> 02:49.537
Simone, he's dead.

02:49.570 --> 02:52.706
Listen, I am sorry
that the boy is dead,

02:52.740 --> 02:55.276
but he had no business
trying to act.

02:55.309 --> 02:56.510
That's the bottom line.
Mnh.

02:56.543 --> 02:59.613
Dante Smith, reading
for the role of Bartender.

02:59.647 --> 03:01.114
Hey, here's your rum and Coke.

03:01.148 --> 03:04.318
You always order dad drinks?
[ Chuckles ]

03:04.352 --> 03:06.320
Uh, the Bartender instantly
regrets saying that.

03:06.354 --> 03:07.755
Hope she didn't hear him.

03:07.788 --> 03:08.989
[ Rapping ] * Yo, yo

03:09.022 --> 03:11.292
* Make some noise,
repeat after me *

03:11.325 --> 03:13.461
* To be or not to be, my G

03:13.494 --> 03:15.095
* That's the question

03:17.831 --> 03:19.233
52% of men

03:19.267 --> 03:23.070
suffer from some form
of erectile dysfunction.

03:23.103 --> 03:25.806
He had two puncture wounds
on his neck.

03:25.839 --> 03:27.941
He died from exs--
He --

03:27.975 --> 03:29.977
[ Stammers ] Um...

03:30.010 --> 03:32.313
Oh, man,
I can't say that word.

03:32.346 --> 03:33.814
Exsanguination.

03:33.847 --> 03:35.783
It means the victim died
of blood loss.

03:35.816 --> 03:37.585
Interviewer: And how did you
determine that?

03:37.618 --> 03:39.920
Well, blood coagulates
after death, you see,

03:39.953 --> 03:42.555
and you usually you see livor
mortis within a few hours --

03:42.590 --> 03:44.156
it presents itself
like bruising,

03:44.191 --> 03:46.093
mostly in
the lower extremities.

03:46.126 --> 03:48.262
But in this case,
there was none.

03:48.296 --> 03:51.599
Which means whoever killed him
drained the body of blood.

03:51.632 --> 03:53.334
That's right.

03:53.367 --> 03:56.168
The murderer was a vampire.

03:56.203 --> 03:57.838
I knew I had to bring
the Feds in.

03:57.871 --> 04:00.774
They have an agent
who's an expert in the field.

04:00.808 --> 04:03.143
Before I joined the FBI,
I-I played, uh,

04:03.176 --> 04:05.346
vampire detective
Stoker Ramsey

04:05.379 --> 04:07.214
for six years
on "Vampire Cop."

04:07.247 --> 04:09.116
[ Dramatic music plays ]

04:09.149 --> 04:11.319
[ Radio chatter ]

04:11.352 --> 04:13.321
[ Camera shutter clicking ]

04:13.353 --> 04:16.223
Oh, damn, Stoker.
You look deader than our victim.

04:16.255 --> 04:19.393
Ugh. Don't remind me.

04:19.427 --> 04:21.295
What do we got?
[ Sighs ]

04:21.329 --> 04:24.798
Name's Lars Cross. He's a coder
for a tech startup --

04:24.832 --> 04:26.967
a ride share app
that went public last week.

04:27.000 --> 04:30.203
Looks like their IPO wasn't
the only thing making a killing.

04:30.237 --> 04:33.407
I got coffins
bigger than this.

04:33.441 --> 04:36.644
What's a successful coder doing
living in a place like this?

04:36.677 --> 04:38.946
Let's see if your blood memory
will help us find out.

04:38.979 --> 04:42.049
[ Sighs ]

04:42.082 --> 04:46.186
**

04:46.219 --> 04:47.755
[ Sighs ]

04:49.289 --> 04:50.324
Ready?

04:51.759 --> 04:53.193
Yeah.

04:53.226 --> 04:55.796
**

04:55.829 --> 04:57.631
[ Screaming ]

04:57.665 --> 05:03.270
**

05:04.104 --> 05:06.073
[ Groans ]

05:06.106 --> 05:09.877
[ Inhales deeply ]

05:09.910 --> 05:11.111
Stoker?

05:11.144 --> 05:12.780
[ Exhales deeply ]

05:12.813 --> 05:14.247
What did you see?

05:14.281 --> 05:19.152
[ Clears throat ]
Killer came for his phone.

05:19.186 --> 05:21.689
Let's get a warrant
for his cell records.

05:22.756 --> 05:24.492
Brendon: But that doesn't
make me an "expert."

05:24.525 --> 05:27.361
What did I tell you
about dimming your shine?

05:27.395 --> 05:29.697
Stop it.
Okay, l-let me just say this.

05:29.730 --> 05:31.765
My boy here
was a method actor...
Mm-hmm.

05:31.799 --> 05:33.433
...so he learned everything

05:33.467 --> 05:35.302
there is to know
about bloodsuckers.

05:35.335 --> 05:38.271
Read every book, uh,
went to Transylvania --

05:38.305 --> 05:39.507
Tell them, B.

05:39.540 --> 05:42.308
He even got nominated
for two People's Choice Awards,

05:42.342 --> 05:45.312
and remember when you won
that MTV Award for Best Kiss?

05:45.345 --> 05:46.947
[ Laughs ]
Yeah. I-I-I do.

05:46.980 --> 05:50.283
Uh, so, yeah, I-I know a lot
about vampiric lore.

05:50.317 --> 05:52.953
Um...happy? Okay.

05:52.986 --> 05:55.255
So, uh,
when Officer Smitty called me,

05:55.288 --> 05:57.290
I-I took it straight
to our boss.

05:57.324 --> 05:59.560
Interviewer: Tell me about
the Special Investigative Unit?

05:59.593 --> 06:02.663
It's a pilot program
of my design.

06:02.696 --> 06:04.532
I hand-picked this squad
in order to create

06:04.565 --> 06:06.634
a fast-moving,
problem-solving unit.

06:06.667 --> 06:08.969
And one of the perks
is I choose my own cases,

06:09.002 --> 06:10.504
and this one was right
up our alley.

06:10.538 --> 06:11.739
And why was that?

06:11.772 --> 06:14.041
Well, the body was found
in a section of the canyon

06:14.074 --> 06:17.110
that is federal land,
and that's our jurisdiction.

06:17.144 --> 06:19.647
Plus, it was also not
your run-of-the-mill homicide,

06:19.680 --> 06:22.850
so it needed serious
outside-the-box thinkers
in order to solve it.

06:22.883 --> 06:25.318
Interviewer: Are your cellphones
off just in case?

06:25.352 --> 06:27.287
Y-- Uh, yeah. We're good.
We're good to go.

06:27.320 --> 06:28.956
Okay, great.
Then let's go.
Mm-hmm.

06:28.989 --> 06:30.758
What were your first impressions
of the victim?

06:30.791 --> 06:32.926
Uh, well, the victim
had old bruises,

06:32.960 --> 06:35.763
collapsed veins, and track marks
all over his arms --

06:35.796 --> 06:38.766
telltale signs
of intravenous drug use.

06:38.799 --> 06:40.701
I-I'm a profiler
by training,

06:40.734 --> 06:43.604
and I built a preliminary theory
that Dante had developed

06:43.637 --> 06:45.706
a serious drug habit
and lived on the streets,

06:45.739 --> 06:48.308
which, of course, would explain
his eight-month disappearance.

06:48.341 --> 06:51.178
But we had to throw that theory
out once the report came back

06:51.211 --> 06:52.613
from Dante's tox screen.

06:52.646 --> 06:54.948
Yeah, he had no signs
of any drugs in his system.

06:54.982 --> 06:57.117
In fact, at the time
of his death,

06:57.150 --> 06:59.219
Dante
was in perfect health.

06:59.252 --> 07:02.590
Were you able to build a profile
of who the killer might've been?

07:02.623 --> 07:04.224
No.

07:04.257 --> 07:05.959
Not at that time.

07:05.993 --> 07:07.828
Interviewer:
You investigated Dante's death,

07:07.861 --> 07:09.830
and your unit never
gave credence

07:09.863 --> 07:12.165
to the possibility
of a supernatural suspect?

07:12.199 --> 07:13.701
Supernatural?

07:13.734 --> 07:16.504
You mean like vampires
or something, right?

07:16.537 --> 07:18.672
Is that --
You said you built a team
of outside-the-box thinkers.

07:18.706 --> 07:20.774
Did you
at least consider it?

07:20.808 --> 07:24.678
[ Clears throat ] Okay, let's,
uh -- let's play your game.

07:25.879 --> 07:29.249
In any vampiric folklore, hmm,
when has a bloodsucker

07:29.282 --> 07:31.018
ever kidnapped someone
for eight months

07:31.051 --> 07:34.588
and then -- only then --
drank their blood?

07:34.622 --> 07:37.224
So that's a no,
you never considered it?

07:37.257 --> 07:39.893
No. I didn't.

07:39.927 --> 07:40.894
Perhaps you should have.

07:40.928 --> 07:42.462
[ Stammers ]

07:42.496 --> 07:44.732
Interviewer: Tell me, Brendon,
why didn't you disclose

07:44.765 --> 07:46.734
that you had a conflict
of interest in the case?

07:46.767 --> 07:48.502
A conflict of in--
interest?

07:48.536 --> 07:50.571
Uh, no, I-I don't.

07:50.604 --> 07:52.372
W-What are you talking
about?

07:52.405 --> 07:54.341
Brendon knew
the murder victim.

07:54.374 --> 07:56.443
We have a photo.
What?

07:56.476 --> 07:57.645
Let me see that.

07:57.678 --> 08:00.247
This was taken at a nightclub
about a year ago.

08:00.280 --> 08:02.850
There's you, and there's
Dante Smith, the victim.

08:02.883 --> 08:04.852
Huh.
That is him, B.

08:04.885 --> 08:07.320
Yeah, that's weird.
I-I never met him.

08:07.354 --> 08:08.756
You sure about that?

08:08.789 --> 08:10.423
Uh...yeah.

08:10.457 --> 08:13.226
I mean, if he said he --
he doesn't know him,
he doesn't know him.

08:13.260 --> 08:15.929
Right, that's a picture of
a drunken me at a nightclub

08:15.963 --> 08:17.164
and another guy.

08:17.197 --> 08:19.266
So, you know, it's a good
old-fashioned...

08:19.299 --> 08:20.300
Coincidence.coincidence.

08:20.332 --> 08:22.435
That was no coincidence.

08:22.469 --> 08:24.404
Brendon Acres
isn't who he claims to be.

08:24.437 --> 08:25.739
Interviewer:
Then who is he?

08:25.773 --> 08:28.275
A corpse with the blood
of human victims

08:28.308 --> 08:29.877
coursing through his body.

08:29.910 --> 08:32.479
Have you seen
"Vampire Cop"?

08:32.511 --> 08:34.815
No way an actor
could be that convincing.

08:34.847 --> 08:37.384
[ Dramatic music plays ]

08:37.417 --> 08:45.793
**

08:45.826 --> 08:47.527
Stoker:
This ends tonight, Albus.

08:47.561 --> 08:50.130
If you were a smart man,
you'd get out of the way.

08:50.163 --> 08:51.732
Too bad
I'm not a smart man.

08:51.765 --> 08:53.133
[ Gunshots ]

08:53.165 --> 08:54.668
[ Grunts ]

08:54.702 --> 08:57.605
[ Exhales deeply ]

08:57.638 --> 09:03.243
**

09:03.276 --> 09:08.782
**

09:08.816 --> 09:10.017
What are you?

09:11.752 --> 09:13.453
Justice.

09:13.486 --> 09:14.955
[ Hisses ]

09:14.988 --> 09:18.926
[ Screaming ]

09:20.894 --> 09:23.263
[ Exhales deeply ]

09:26.667 --> 09:29.737
Had to learn the hard way --

09:29.770 --> 09:31.204
crime sucks.

09:31.238 --> 09:34.540
No way that's an act.
Brendon is the real thing.

09:34.574 --> 09:36.710
Is my son a real vampire?

09:36.744 --> 09:38.178
Well,
I'll tell you one thing --

09:38.211 --> 09:39.747
his mom was a complete
horror show

09:39.780 --> 09:41.481
who drained me financially.

09:41.514 --> 09:43.383
Interviewer: So there's nothing
that supports the accusations

09:43.415 --> 09:45.485
that Brendon is, in fact,
a vampire?

09:45.518 --> 09:47.387
Well, since I knew
you'd be asking,

09:47.420 --> 09:49.690
I brought his baby teeth.

09:49.723 --> 09:51.692
Look at those canines
right there.

09:51.725 --> 09:54.227
That little ragamuffin could
tear through a steak at age 2.

09:54.261 --> 09:56.063
Okay, okay. What are you doing?
What are you do--

09:56.096 --> 09:57.330
I'm telling --
telling the truth.
Okay, that's enough.

09:57.364 --> 09:59.066
That's enough.
Please. Thank you.

09:59.099 --> 10:00.701
That's a wrap.
That's a wrap.
Okay.

10:00.734 --> 10:01.935
Let's go.
Okay.

10:01.969 --> 10:03.637
What are you doing?
Okay, I'm -- I'm --

10:03.671 --> 10:04.905
I'm leaning into
the controversy.
You can't just make
that stuff up.

10:04.938 --> 10:06.807
People are gonna believe it.
People are gonna believe it.

10:06.840 --> 10:08.575
Let's go.
Well, listen,
it's great TV, man.

10:08.608 --> 10:10.143
Let's --
It'll put you back
in the zeitgeist.

10:10.177 --> 10:11.411
I don't want to be
in the zeitgeist.

10:11.444 --> 10:12.646
I don't want to be
in the zeitgeist.

10:12.680 --> 10:14.181
Yeah, okay.
And where did you get
these teeth?

10:14.214 --> 10:15.816
Uh, I know a guy.
What?

10:15.849 --> 10:17.050
You want some?
Ew.

10:17.084 --> 10:18.585
Interviewer: How do you respond
to allegations

10:18.618 --> 10:20.387
that Brendon Acres
is a vampire?

10:20.420 --> 10:22.122
[ Chuckles ]

10:22.155 --> 10:25.525
Um, well, as Brendon's
training agent,

10:25.558 --> 10:27.394
and as a rational
human being,

10:27.427 --> 10:29.296
I can confirm
he's not a vampire.

10:29.329 --> 10:30.831
My ex-wife grew up
in New Orleans,

10:30.864 --> 10:32.165
and I worked there
for years,

10:32.199 --> 10:34.201
so I've heard all
of the vampire lore,

10:34.234 --> 10:36.036
and these are
just stories.

10:36.069 --> 10:38.338
Zero evidence
it's even possible.

10:38.371 --> 10:40.240
Hmm.

10:40.273 --> 10:41.709
Hmm?
Did you say, "Hmm"?

10:41.742 --> 10:44.011
Yeah. Just interesting hearing
such skepticism,

10:44.044 --> 10:47.014
from someone who believes in,
um...

10:47.047 --> 10:49.182
Bigfoot.
Well, that's different.

10:49.216 --> 10:50.583
Bigfoot's real.

10:50.617 --> 10:52.019
Unh-unh.

10:52.052 --> 10:54.922
Whatever you do,
don't get Carter started

10:54.955 --> 10:56.189
talking about Skookum.

10:56.223 --> 10:57.557
Well, the thing
about Bigfoot is --

10:57.590 --> 11:00.794
You know, I really think that
we should just stay on topic.

11:00.828 --> 11:02.896
You know,
about the murder.

11:02.930 --> 11:05.532
Okay, but...
let's pick this up later?

11:05.565 --> 11:07.200
Uh, yeah.

11:08.902 --> 11:11.404
Okay, anyway,
statistically speaking,

11:11.438 --> 11:13.707
murderers usually bury
and dump bodies

11:13.741 --> 11:15.776
in places they know,
live, or frequent.

11:15.809 --> 11:19.079
So we began the investigation
where Dante's body was found.

11:19.112 --> 11:21.381
And after canvassing
the neighborhood, we, uh,

11:21.414 --> 11:24.084
spoke to several residents
who all pointed to one man.

11:24.117 --> 11:25.552
Anders Huxley.

11:25.585 --> 11:28.321
Uh, he had an extensive
rap sheet --

11:28.355 --> 11:30.791
assault, battery,
public intoxication.

11:30.824 --> 11:34.361
Word was Mr. Huxley
only went out at night --

11:34.394 --> 11:36.629
which is an opportune time
to bury a body.

11:36.663 --> 11:38.031
So we paid him a visit.

11:38.065 --> 11:41.101
Though, in retrospect,
we probably should have waited

11:41.134 --> 11:43.136
until daylight.
Mm, yes.

11:43.170 --> 11:46.774
[ Dramatic music plays ]

11:46.807 --> 11:52.379
**

11:52.412 --> 11:54.081
Alright.

11:55.648 --> 11:57.584
Is that blood?

11:57.617 --> 11:59.486
Carter:
Yeah, that's blood.

11:59.519 --> 12:00.888
Laura: Door's ajar.

12:00.921 --> 12:03.123
Does the blood give us PC
to go inside?

12:03.156 --> 12:06.659
Someone may be in imminent
danger, so, yeah, it does.

12:06.693 --> 12:08.762
[ Knock on door ]

12:08.796 --> 12:11.198
FBI!
Anyone in there?

12:11.231 --> 12:17.037
**

12:17.070 --> 12:20.140
Mr. Huxley?
Anyone here?

12:20.173 --> 12:23.010
Simone:
Carter. More blood.

12:23.043 --> 12:24.477
Brendon: Let's go up.

12:24.511 --> 12:34.121
**

12:34.154 --> 12:35.622
Good?

12:35.655 --> 12:45.098
**

12:45.132 --> 12:46.099
Brendon: Is he breathing?

12:46.133 --> 12:47.600
Carter: Is he dead?

12:47.634 --> 12:48.836
Simone: I don't know.

12:48.869 --> 12:51.138
Mr. Huxley?

12:51.171 --> 12:53.406
[ Screams ]
Oh, my God!
FBI!

12:57.777 --> 12:59.146
Brendon: Oh, my God!

12:59.179 --> 13:00.480
Carter: FBI!
Hands where we can see them!

13:00.513 --> 13:02.482
I mean, none of us
really believed Anders

13:02.515 --> 13:04.751
was actually a vampire.

13:04.784 --> 13:06.786
Carter: Pale skin, sharp teeth,
red eyes --

13:06.820 --> 13:10.190
He did have some attributes
that might lead one to assume

13:10.223 --> 13:11.624
he was a creature
of the night.

13:11.658 --> 13:13.526
Am I being SWAT-ed?

13:13.560 --> 13:15.562
I've read about this.

13:15.595 --> 13:18.098
People make a fake 911 call
as a prank

13:18.131 --> 13:20.167
to get the cops
to raid a house.

13:20.200 --> 13:21.201
Brendon:
It's not a prank.

13:21.234 --> 13:22.669
Why are you here?

13:22.702 --> 13:24.704
We just wanted to ask a few
questions about a murder victim

13:24.737 --> 13:26.139
we found near here.

13:26.173 --> 13:27.774
Let me guess.

13:27.807 --> 13:30.677
All the neighbors said
it was me.

13:30.710 --> 13:34.581
Just because I'm different, it
doesn't mean that I'm a killer.

13:34.614 --> 13:36.716
I have porphyria.

13:36.749 --> 13:38.518
It's been called
"vampire's disease."

13:38.551 --> 13:40.854
It's like a blood disorder
that affects the skin.

13:40.888 --> 13:43.156
But you know more about it.
T-Tell him, B.

13:43.190 --> 13:44.657
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
So, porphyria --

13:44.691 --> 13:48.128
people with this condition have
a severe aversion to sunlight.

13:48.161 --> 13:49.930
Also, it can lead
to gum recession,

13:49.963 --> 13:52.032
so the --
the teeth show more.

13:52.065 --> 13:54.334
They look like --
you know, like fangs.

13:54.367 --> 13:56.103
And then tell him about
Count Dracula.

13:56.136 --> 13:58.571
Yeah, the Romanian Prince
Vlad the Impaler,

13:58.605 --> 14:00.874
a.k.a. Vlad Dracula,
Count Dracula --

14:00.908 --> 14:02.609
he -- he apparently
had porphyria.

14:02.642 --> 14:04.344
Left untreated,
it -- it -- it causes,

14:04.377 --> 14:08.481
uh, massive, uh, paranoia,
hallucinations.

14:08.515 --> 14:10.650
Vlad apparently thought everyone
was, like, after him.

14:10.683 --> 14:14.254
So he would just [hisses]
kill them first.

14:14.287 --> 14:15.788
Interviewer: And is that
why you thought Anders Huxley

14:15.822 --> 14:17.624
killed Dante Smith?

14:18.625 --> 14:20.293
Anders:
I didn't kill anyone.

14:20.327 --> 14:22.795
And an unfounded allegation
does not give you the right

14:22.829 --> 14:24.431
to charge into my home.

14:24.464 --> 14:27.367
Well, we saw a trail of blood.
That's why we came in.

14:27.400 --> 14:28.801
What happened
to your hand?

14:28.835 --> 14:31.638
I caught it in an Uber door
this morning.

14:31.671 --> 14:33.040
Blood everywhere.

14:33.073 --> 14:34.274
So, why didn't you clean up
the blood?

14:34.307 --> 14:36.276
I was just so damn
jet-lagged.

14:36.309 --> 14:38.545
Turns out,
Huxley had an alibi.

14:38.578 --> 14:40.080
Where were you
last night?

14:40.113 --> 14:43.116
On a plane,
flying back from a work trip.

14:43.150 --> 14:46.653
My condition means I try
to avoid being awake

14:46.686 --> 14:47.887
when the sun is up.

14:47.921 --> 14:50.023
You wouldn't believe what
our alleged vampire

14:50.057 --> 14:51.258
did for a living.

14:54.761 --> 14:57.130
I'm a children's book author
and illustrator.

14:57.164 --> 14:59.466
Wait. You're the author of
"Alistair the Aye Aye"?

14:59.499 --> 15:02.535
Yes, and I used to read
his books to my son, Isaiah,

15:02.569 --> 15:04.171
when he was a kid.

15:04.204 --> 15:06.273
Alistair was always teased
because he was different

15:06.306 --> 15:07.640
from all the other
animals.

15:07.674 --> 15:10.043
But then he'd teach them
that differences

15:10.077 --> 15:12.179
were what made each of them
special.

15:12.212 --> 15:15.782
Anders turned his own experience
of being ostracized

15:15.815 --> 15:18.685
for his condition into
a hit children's book series.

15:18.718 --> 15:21.989
So we apologized to Mr. Huxley
for the intrusion.

15:22.022 --> 15:25.192
And he was really kind
and forgiving about
the whole mix-up,

15:25.225 --> 15:26.926
just like Alistair the Aye Aye
is.

15:26.960 --> 15:27.961
He loves that book.

15:27.995 --> 15:29.662
Uh, he even gave us
signed copies.

15:29.696 --> 15:30.930
Yeah, that was nice.

15:30.964 --> 15:32.365
[ Chuckles ]

15:32.399 --> 15:33.766
Interviewer:
Are federal employees allowed

15:33.800 --> 15:35.402
to receive gifts?

15:38.538 --> 15:40.807
Interviewer:
So, Mr. Huxley wasn't a vampire
or the killer after all.

15:40.840 --> 15:42.875
That is correct, which is why
we could officially put

15:42.909 --> 15:45.345
this ridiculous vampire theory
to rest,

15:45.378 --> 15:47.680
once the Medical Examiner
finished her report.

15:47.714 --> 15:49.149
Is that when you realized

15:49.182 --> 15:50.883
you might have a serial killer
on your hands?

15:50.917 --> 15:53.053
Well, a body
completely drained of blood,

15:53.086 --> 15:54.621
buried in the hills
above Nichols Canyon --

15:54.654 --> 15:55.922
It -- It did.

15:55.955 --> 15:58.558
It had commonality with the M.O.
of the Canyon Killer.

15:58.591 --> 16:00.693
Great.
I mean, not great

16:00.727 --> 16:02.162
it was a serial killer
involved,

16:02.195 --> 16:03.563
but great
that you had a lead.

16:03.596 --> 16:05.498
Oh, no, no, no. There's just --
There's a problem here.

16:05.532 --> 16:06.866
You see,
the Canyon Killer

16:06.899 --> 16:08.735
couldn't have done it
because he's in prison.

16:08.768 --> 16:11.338
Put there by one
of your own agents.

16:11.371 --> 16:13.373
Isn't that right?
Yeah. That's right.

16:13.406 --> 16:16.043
I caught
the Canyon Killer.

16:16.076 --> 16:18.611
We caught
the Canyon Killer.

16:18.645 --> 16:20.580
Ah, yes.
Interviewer: And you are?

16:20.613 --> 16:24.251
Special Agent Mark Atlas. FBI.
Behavioral Science Unit.

16:24.284 --> 16:25.752
We led the investigation
together.

16:25.785 --> 16:26.919
Which was built
on my profile.

16:26.953 --> 16:28.021
She gave
some of the clues.

16:29.656 --> 16:31.424
Okay, you gave
the important ones.

16:31.458 --> 16:32.992
And what were the clues?

16:33.026 --> 16:35.428
Well, the Canyon Killer's
first victims were found

16:35.462 --> 16:37.997
in the Hollywood Hills
in the summer of 2018.

16:38.031 --> 16:40.367
Uh, all victims had evidence
of being bound by the wrists,

16:40.400 --> 16:42.735
and they were drained of blood
before they were buried.

16:42.769 --> 16:45.838
So while Agent Atlas was focused
on the killer's M.O.,

16:45.872 --> 16:48.875
I gathered details on the
victims and retraced their steps

16:48.908 --> 16:50.443
before their time of death.

16:50.477 --> 16:52.712
You both seem very pleased
with yourselves.

16:52.745 --> 16:54.614
Do -- Do -- Do your colleagues
find that annoying?

16:56.116 --> 16:59.286
Uh, I can be very passionate
about what I do.

16:59.319 --> 17:01.421
That's a way to put it.
I take a lot of pride
in profiling.

17:01.454 --> 17:04.156
Hmm.
Um, and some people may feel
like that steps on their toes,

17:04.191 --> 17:05.858
but that's not my problem.

17:07.827 --> 17:08.994
She's a little annoying.

17:09.028 --> 17:12.132
The Canyon Killer
made national headlines.

17:12.165 --> 17:13.965
I followed the story
in D.C.

17:14.000 --> 17:16.336
I was calling my dad every night
to check in,

17:16.368 --> 17:19.271
because Los Angeles was --
it was on edge.

17:19.306 --> 17:20.973
Mm-hmm.
I mean, you were here
at that time, B.

17:21.007 --> 17:22.541
Were you scared?
Oh, my God, yeah.

17:22.575 --> 17:25.412
Me -- Me and my friends,
we stopped clubbing for weeks.

17:25.444 --> 17:27.614
I mean, we fit
the victim's profile perfectly.

17:27.646 --> 17:30.117
You know, like, young,
super hot guys

17:30.150 --> 17:31.851
with, uh, h-hairless...

17:33.886 --> 17:35.622
That sounded pretentious.
Can, uh --

17:35.655 --> 17:37.023
Who cares?
No, it's --

17:37.056 --> 17:39.259
Tell your truth.
If you're cute, you're cute.

17:39.292 --> 17:40.627
Can you just --
If you're hot, you're hot,

17:40.660 --> 17:41.928
and if you're not,
you're not.

17:41.961 --> 17:43.196
Right.
So, we're gonna cut that?

17:43.230 --> 17:44.297
Interviewer: Oh, yeah.
Leave it in.
Thank you.

17:44.331 --> 17:45.498
Sure, no problem.
Leave it in.
No.

17:45.532 --> 17:47.534
Interviewer: I really like
that target on your wall.

17:47.567 --> 17:49.669
Did you actually fire the
bullets that went through that,

17:49.702 --> 17:52.305
or did you just stab it
with a pen and hang it up?

17:52.339 --> 17:54.241
I, uh...

17:54.274 --> 17:57.076
I won it in a raffle.
[ Clears throat ]

17:57.110 --> 18:00.280
So, um, did you work
the Canyon Killer investigation?

18:00.313 --> 18:02.882
I consulted with Laura
and Mark Atlas

18:02.915 --> 18:04.417
on the Canyon Killer
task force.

18:04.451 --> 18:06.486
It's where I first saw Laura
in action on a case,

18:06.519 --> 18:08.087
and she was brilliant.

18:08.121 --> 18:10.523
No stone left unturned.

18:10.557 --> 18:12.692
Which is why I eventually
asked her to join my squad.

18:12.725 --> 18:14.161
It was a complex profile.

18:14.194 --> 18:15.462
You made it look easy.

18:15.495 --> 18:17.697
Oh. You delivered
great evidence.

18:17.730 --> 18:19.031
Thank you.

18:19.065 --> 18:20.733
[ Chuckles ] At first,
the Canyon killer

18:20.767 --> 18:23.636
was meticulous, but then,
after the sixth body,

18:23.670 --> 18:25.205
got sloppy.

18:25.238 --> 18:27.540
They all do.They all do.

18:29.008 --> 18:30.843
[ Chuckles ]
[ Chuckles ]

18:30.877 --> 18:31.844
Sorry, you go --
You want to go?

18:31.878 --> 18:32.845
No, you go.

18:32.879 --> 18:34.647
Well, you should start.
Okay.

18:34.681 --> 18:36.983
Um, where should we start?
The -- The victimology?

18:37.016 --> 18:38.751
The victimology, yes. So --
Then you got to go.

18:38.785 --> 18:40.487
Alright, well, we, um --
That's you.

18:40.520 --> 18:42.922
[ Clears throat ] We realized
that he was gregarious,

18:42.955 --> 18:44.457
and probably attractive
himself.

18:44.491 --> 18:45.958
It's why he felt he could
approach his victims

18:45.992 --> 18:47.360
with such ease.

18:47.394 --> 18:49.162
He ran in the same circle
as they did.

18:49.196 --> 18:51.631
And we figured he worked
in the service industry...
Mm-hmm.

18:51.664 --> 18:55.335
...like many of his victims --
all aspiring actors or models.

18:55.368 --> 18:57.737
And then on top of that,
all of his victims lived

18:57.770 --> 19:00.039
or worked near
the Franklin corridor.

19:00.072 --> 19:02.609
See? Just there.

19:02.642 --> 19:03.910
And then
on the seventh murder...

19:03.943 --> 19:05.812
Ohh.
...we caught a break.

19:05.845 --> 19:08.548
Forensics discovered primo trace
evidence at that crime scene.

19:08.581 --> 19:10.383
Mm-hmm.
Purple wig hair.

19:10.417 --> 19:12.652
Yes, but not just
any purple wig.

19:12.685 --> 19:14.987
This was a custom job
with real human hair

19:15.021 --> 19:16.989
that had been
professionally dyed.

19:17.023 --> 19:18.525
It was a signature
headpiece.

19:18.558 --> 19:20.560
That's what I thought.
Hollywood bull's-eye, baby.

19:20.593 --> 19:22.462
Bam.
Interviewer: Is that a term?

19:22.495 --> 19:24.063
Is that a thing, a real thing,
or are you just making that up?

19:24.096 --> 19:25.965
Well, you know what I'm saying.
It's like a --
Like "nailed it."

19:25.998 --> 19:27.434
Yeah, nailed it.
That's what I'm trying to say.

19:27.467 --> 19:29.135
[ Microphone feedback ]

19:29.168 --> 19:32.339
Now, we've pulled over here
because you do not want to miss

19:32.372 --> 19:33.773
what is on your right.

19:33.806 --> 19:35.742
Across the street from
the famed Bronson Gate

19:35.775 --> 19:37.944
is the apartment building
where Bela Lugosi,

19:37.977 --> 19:39.646
the world's most famous
Dracula,

19:39.679 --> 19:42.715
died of a heart attack in 1956.

19:42.749 --> 19:46.653
Now, Lugosi was found in his
bed, naked, clutching a script

19:46.686 --> 19:49.956
to "The Final Curtain," a, uh,
movie he was set to star in

19:49.989 --> 19:52.925
for schlock film maestro
Ed Wood.

19:52.959 --> 19:55.094
Gulliver Farris?
We need to talk.

19:55.127 --> 19:57.664
[ Crowd murmuring ]

20:00.400 --> 20:02.369
Hands behind your back.

20:02.402 --> 20:05.372
Okay. FBI.
Put the phones down, please.

20:05.405 --> 20:08.308
Thank you. We'll get you
on the road soon enough.

20:08.341 --> 20:09.709
Mm.
That was a good day.

20:09.742 --> 20:11.778
Yeah, it was probably
one of our best.
Mm.

20:11.811 --> 20:14.614
We gave the victims' families
closure,

20:14.647 --> 20:17.384
let the people of Los Angeles
rest their fears,

20:17.417 --> 20:19.419
and put a monster
behind bars.

20:19.452 --> 20:20.887
I'm an innocent man.

20:20.920 --> 20:22.989
Interviewer:
Of this current murder, perhaps.

20:23.022 --> 20:24.757
But it's interesting how
Dante Smith died

20:24.791 --> 20:27.760
in the exact same way
as you killed your victims.

20:27.794 --> 20:29.696
Do you think you have
a copycat?

20:29.729 --> 20:33.065
No. Because I've never killed
anyone.

20:33.099 --> 20:34.301
Ever.

20:34.334 --> 20:35.702
What exactly
are you saying?

20:35.735 --> 20:37.537
That I'm not
the Canyon Killer.

20:37.570 --> 20:39.906
I've only been saying that
since my arrest.

20:39.939 --> 20:42.375
Special Agent Laura Stensen
framed me.

20:42.409 --> 20:44.010
I'm at the center

20:44.043 --> 20:47.414
of the biggest FBI cover-up
since Bigfoot.

20:47.447 --> 20:51.284
And -- And how's this for
your little, uh, TV program --

20:51.318 --> 20:52.785
I have proof.

20:52.819 --> 20:54.554
That's ridiculous.

20:54.587 --> 20:56.122
Yes, of course he says
he's innocent.

20:56.155 --> 20:57.457
They all do.They all do.

20:57.490 --> 21:00.327
[ Dramatic music plays ]

21:00.360 --> 21:03.095
I-I did not frame
Mr. Farris.

21:03.129 --> 21:04.431
Interviewer:
So you've said,

21:04.464 --> 21:06.666
but I've seen the evidence,
and it's quite damning.

21:06.699 --> 21:09.101
Which means the real killer
could still be out there.

21:09.135 --> 21:11.538
And if he is, then the blood
of this newest victim --

21:11.571 --> 21:14.073
well, that's on your hands.

21:18.778 --> 21:21.013
Are you suggesting that
Special Agents Stensen and Atlas

21:21.047 --> 21:22.482
framed a serial killer?

21:22.515 --> 21:23.716
Interviewer: I'm just looking
for the truth.

21:23.750 --> 21:25.518
No. No, you're not.

21:25.552 --> 21:27.219
You're fishing
for provocative sound bites

21:27.253 --> 21:29.522
that you can edit
out of context. Hmm?

21:29.556 --> 21:32.124
Anything to make this little
documentary of yours, uh,

21:32.158 --> 21:34.661
I don't know,
a bit more salacious.

21:34.694 --> 21:37.029
This isn't some news mag
with gotcha questions.

21:37.063 --> 21:38.865
I'm an award-winning
documentarian.

21:38.898 --> 21:41.167
Film is my medium.
I deal in truth.

21:41.200 --> 21:42.301
Yeah, right.

21:42.335 --> 21:43.970
Look, I don't appreciate
what you're insinuating.

21:44.003 --> 21:45.438
Especially when we have
the proof.

21:45.472 --> 21:47.173
No, you don't.
We do.

21:47.206 --> 21:50.009
Overwhelming evidence
that proves that Mr. Farris

21:50.042 --> 21:51.944
was the one and only
Canyon Killer.

21:51.978 --> 21:53.346
And how dare you, huh?

21:53.380 --> 21:55.314
How dare you disparage
Laura Stensen's good name.

21:55.348 --> 21:59.952
She is one the finest FBI agents
to ever carry the badge.

21:59.986 --> 22:01.053
Gulliver:
She's a train wreck.

22:01.087 --> 22:03.022
My lawyer found evidence

22:03.055 --> 22:05.124
that she was, uh,
mentally unstable

22:05.157 --> 22:06.659
around the time
she arrested me.

22:06.693 --> 22:09.261
Wait, you've been screwing
my best friend behind my back

22:09.295 --> 22:11.364
for months, and somehow
that's my fault?

22:11.398 --> 22:13.566
[ Scoffs ] No, I never want
to see your face again.

22:13.600 --> 22:15.334
Do you hear me?
Never!

22:15.368 --> 22:17.937
You're such a [bleep]

22:17.970 --> 22:22.341
Get your stuff out of my condo
right now!

22:22.375 --> 22:24.944
Do you hear me,
you piece of [bleep]
Laur--

22:24.977 --> 22:26.879
[ Breathing heavily ]

22:26.913 --> 22:28.581
Maybe just relax
a second, okay?

22:28.615 --> 22:30.249
I can't relax!
Ohh!

22:30.282 --> 22:32.552
[ Clattering ]

22:32.585 --> 22:33.920
What, Kristal?!

22:33.953 --> 22:36.889
Do you really trust this woman
to catch a serial murderer

22:36.923 --> 22:38.858
when she couldn't even
tell her own fiancé

22:38.891 --> 22:40.226
was stepping out on her?

22:40.259 --> 22:43.696
Agent Stensen was --
was too busy spiraling
to solve the case.

22:43.730 --> 22:45.432
I'm the real victim here.

22:45.465 --> 22:46.899
Okay, yes, fine.

22:46.933 --> 22:48.701
At the time of Mr. Farris'
arrest,

22:48.735 --> 22:51.604
my personal life
was...challenged,

22:51.638 --> 22:54.874
but that in no way affected
my performance at work.

22:54.907 --> 22:56.075
Not at all.

22:56.108 --> 22:58.077
Of course it did.

22:58.110 --> 23:00.580
She got fired from the BSU
right after her meltdown.

23:00.613 --> 23:04.316
But to keep her from losing
her job, they conspired

23:04.350 --> 23:06.986
and, uh, falsified evidence
against me.

23:07.019 --> 23:11.023
Interviewer: Wait, who are
you saying conspired with her?

23:11.057 --> 23:13.960
Special Agent Mark Atlas.

23:13.993 --> 23:15.261
That's a wild accusation.

23:15.294 --> 23:17.396
Why would Agent Atlas
do that?

23:17.430 --> 23:20.232
If it looks like a duck
and it quacks like a duck...

23:20.266 --> 23:22.669
Those two FBI agents
are having sex.

23:22.702 --> 23:26.138
Interviewer: Agent Atlas, did
you conspire with Agent Stensen

23:26.172 --> 23:28.808
because of a secret
romantic relationship?

23:28.841 --> 23:30.910
Nothing could be further
from the truth.

23:30.943 --> 23:32.512
So you didn't cover
for Agent Stensen?

23:32.545 --> 23:33.780
No. Of course not.

23:33.813 --> 23:35.515
And are you having
a secret romance?

23:35.548 --> 23:38.485
Okay, e-enough
with this tabloid BS. I --

23:38.518 --> 23:39.986
Excuse me?

23:40.019 --> 23:42.021
All of these questions
about our personal life --

23:42.054 --> 23:43.690
it's utterly shameful.
Hmm.

23:43.723 --> 23:45.191
So, you're denying
your affair?

23:45.224 --> 23:47.560
Can we just stop the cameras
from rolling right now?

23:47.594 --> 23:48.628
I just need a minute.

23:48.661 --> 23:49.796
You okay?
Yeah, fine.

23:49.829 --> 23:51.464
Can you just come with me,
please?

23:51.498 --> 23:53.332
Uh...I'm gonna --
We can take a break.

23:53.365 --> 23:55.134
Yeah. Thank you.

23:55.167 --> 23:56.903
Just -- Yeah.

23:56.936 --> 23:58.404
Keep rolling.

24:06.846 --> 24:09.148
But we are having sex.
[ Sighs ]

24:09.181 --> 24:10.449
We could be having
more sex.

24:17.289 --> 24:18.925
Just tell them
that then.

24:23.596 --> 24:25.832
Okay. Well...

24:30.236 --> 24:32.171
I do.
What?

24:32.204 --> 24:34.140
I do have my mic on.

24:34.173 --> 24:35.407
**

24:35.441 --> 24:37.977
Uh-oh.

24:38.010 --> 24:39.011
Excuse me, what?

24:39.045 --> 24:43.215
My Atlas and --
and, uh, Laura.

24:43.249 --> 24:45.217
I definitely didn't know that,
no.

24:45.251 --> 24:46.485
Why didn't he tell me?

24:46.519 --> 24:47.820
Wait, did you know?

24:49.689 --> 24:50.890
Yeah.
What?

24:50.923 --> 24:51.924
I mean, I knew, yes.

24:51.958 --> 24:54.961
A-And I am 100%
on Team Laura.

24:54.994 --> 24:57.196
I mean,
she finally getting some.

24:57.229 --> 24:58.631
When you say romantically,
you mean like --

24:58.665 --> 24:59.799
[ Laughs ]

24:59.832 --> 25:01.734
Somebody is jealous.
[ Giggles ]

25:01.768 --> 25:03.069
Huh.

25:03.102 --> 25:05.772
And then the case of
the Mudslide Marauder took a --

25:05.805 --> 25:07.373
Interviewer: Wait a second.
Mudslide Marauder?

25:07.406 --> 25:08.641
No one calls it that.

25:08.675 --> 25:11.043
On "Smitty's Streets"
they do.

25:11.077 --> 25:13.880
Your claims of patsies
and copycat killers --

25:13.913 --> 25:15.615
you know, it may help boost
ratings,

25:15.648 --> 25:18.885
but it's irresponsible to
cast aspersions on my people

25:18.918 --> 25:20.486
and the FBI.

25:20.519 --> 25:23.422
Dante Smith's murderer
wasn't the Canyon Killer,

25:23.455 --> 25:25.424
and you know that.

25:25.457 --> 25:27.594
So stop creating a narrative
that never existed.

25:27.627 --> 25:30.697
It's lazy storytelling,
and you're better than that.

25:30.730 --> 25:32.599
Interviewer: Fine.
You were saying?

25:32.632 --> 25:36.703
The case of the
Mudslide Marauder took a turn.

25:46.979 --> 25:50.116
So, the M.E. came in to work
that morning

25:50.149 --> 25:52.218
to do the autopsy
on Dante Smith's body.

25:52.251 --> 25:53.720
And, uh...
It was gone.

25:53.753 --> 25:54.987
Body gone.

25:55.021 --> 25:58.958
And last I checked, dead bodies
do not move themselves.

25:58.991 --> 26:00.860
The undead do.

26:00.893 --> 26:02.829
Interviewer: Officer Smitty,
what are you saying?

26:02.862 --> 26:05.798
What everybody's thinking --
Dante, the victim,

26:05.832 --> 26:07.133
took a turn --

26:07.166 --> 26:09.969
became a vampire
and escaped.

26:10.002 --> 26:11.804
Seriously? You're still on
the vampire thing?

26:11.838 --> 26:13.840
[ Dramatic music plays ]

26:13.873 --> 26:15.507
That's not at all
what happened.

26:15.541 --> 26:17.509
Earlier that morning,
someone broke into the morgue

26:17.543 --> 26:18.778
and stole his body.

26:18.811 --> 26:22.514
[ Dramatic music plays ]

26:22.548 --> 26:26.118
I suppose I could speculate
as to why someone would steal

26:26.152 --> 26:28.287
a dead body from a morgue
before it had even been

26:28.320 --> 26:31.691
autopsied and processed
for forensic evidence, but...

26:31.724 --> 26:34.593
But the odds were, whoever
took him out...took him out.

26:37.930 --> 26:39.699
Interviewer: So, your suspect
got away with Dante's body.

26:39.732 --> 26:41.100
How did he pull that off?

26:41.133 --> 26:43.369
Our subject was able to walk out
of the medical examiner's office

26:43.402 --> 26:46.305
with Dante's body
by impersonating
a morgue attendant.

26:46.338 --> 26:47.774
He was smart enough
to cover his face

26:47.807 --> 26:49.241
from all
the surveillance cameras,

26:49.275 --> 26:52.344
but not smart enough to cover
the license plate on his car.

26:52.378 --> 26:55.982
Which was registered to our
body snatcher -- Jake Alpert.

26:56.015 --> 26:58.517
So my team went to go pay him
a visit.

26:58.550 --> 27:01.921
[ Dramatic music plays ]

27:01.954 --> 27:02.989
**

27:03.022 --> 27:04.724
Carter: Jake Alpert,
show us your hands.

27:04.757 --> 27:06.058
Hey!

27:06.092 --> 27:07.660
Cut him off
at the back.

27:07.694 --> 27:11.563
**

27:11.597 --> 27:13.199
Jake!

27:13.232 --> 27:19.138
**

27:19.171 --> 27:24.711
**

27:24.744 --> 27:26.178
Laura:
Where's Dante's body?

27:26.212 --> 27:28.047
I have no idea what
you're talking about.

27:28.080 --> 27:30.616
[ Sighs ]

27:30.649 --> 27:33.019
Carter,
check the freezer.

27:33.052 --> 27:38.457
**

27:38.490 --> 27:40.059
Interviewer:
So who is Jake Alpert?

27:40.092 --> 27:43.262
Jake moved to L.A.
from Montana five years ago.

27:43.295 --> 27:47.333
Spent a year trying to make it
until a modeling scout

27:47.366 --> 27:50.937
saw him working in a Jamba Juice
and plucked him from obscurity.

27:50.970 --> 27:53.940
After that,
he was on a hot streak.

27:53.973 --> 27:56.175
Emphasis on the hot.

27:56.208 --> 27:59.078
Are you seriously trying to
deflect from your relationship

27:59.111 --> 28:00.612
with Atlas like that?
What? No.

28:00.646 --> 28:02.648
Who told you we were
in a relationship?

28:05.451 --> 28:06.585
Uh, really?

28:06.618 --> 28:08.755
Jake was a, you know,
model on the rise.

28:08.788 --> 28:10.489
Worked with all
the big fashion houses.

28:10.522 --> 28:13.625
At the height of his career,
he even dated Layla Laughlin.

28:13.659 --> 28:14.894
Yeah.
Interviewer:
The cosmetics maven?

28:14.927 --> 28:16.996
Founder of
Untold Cosmetics

28:17.029 --> 28:19.698
and the inventor of
de León Miracle Cream.

28:19.732 --> 28:21.467
The woman's an icon.

28:21.500 --> 28:23.502
[ Mid-tempo music plays ]

28:23.535 --> 28:31.944
**

28:31.978 --> 28:40.086
**

28:40.119 --> 28:43.422
De León Miracle Cream.

28:43.455 --> 28:45.257
Ageless.

28:45.291 --> 28:46.725
Timeless.

28:46.759 --> 28:48.560
Beautiful.

28:48.594 --> 28:51.998
By me, Layla Laughlin.

28:52.031 --> 28:53.565
**

28:53.599 --> 28:56.468
Layla was a single mother,
working as a waitress

28:56.502 --> 28:59.438
when she had a dream to start
her own beauty company.

28:59.471 --> 29:02.809
I mean, she used to mix all
her products in her own kitchen,

29:02.842 --> 29:06.412
and then sold them to local moms
out of the back of her minivan.

29:06.445 --> 29:07.513
Interviewer:
You admire her.

29:07.546 --> 29:09.882
What's not to admire?
I mean, she took a risk.

29:09.916 --> 29:13.085
She bet on herself,
built a Fortune 500 company,

29:13.119 --> 29:15.387
all while raising
her son?
Hmm.

29:15.421 --> 29:17.489
Plus, have you seen her?

29:17.523 --> 29:19.425
The girl had looks,
poise,

29:19.458 --> 29:22.161
and always had
a young, hot boy on her side.

29:22.194 --> 29:23.462
[ Laughs ]

29:23.495 --> 29:25.898
She was living her best life
for sure.

29:25.932 --> 29:27.867
And that life included...

29:27.900 --> 29:29.168
Jake, until...

29:29.201 --> 29:31.037
Until it didn't.
Didn't. Right.

29:31.070 --> 29:33.873
Jake was riding high,
until the harsh realities

29:33.906 --> 29:36.242
of the business brought
his dreams crashing down.

29:36.275 --> 29:39.645
He hit 30, and his modeling
contracts dried up.

29:39.678 --> 29:42.548
And Layla left him --
for Dante.

29:42.581 --> 29:44.050
That's right.

29:44.083 --> 29:46.218
Dante was dating
Layla Laughlin

29:46.252 --> 29:48.220
at the time
of his disappearance.

29:48.254 --> 29:50.189
Hey, uh, you're not gonna wait
until like 40 minutes

29:50.222 --> 29:52.825
into this thing to tell the
audience this part, are you?

29:52.859 --> 29:54.326
I hate when docs
do that --

29:54.360 --> 29:56.695
hold back information that the
investigators knew on day one.

29:56.728 --> 29:57.763
Ugh. The worst.

29:57.796 --> 29:59.331
Don't screw
with the audience.

29:59.365 --> 30:01.067
I would never.
Cool.

30:15.347 --> 30:16.849
I was never
at the morgue.

30:16.883 --> 30:18.885
Mm, but we saw you
in the security footage.

30:18.918 --> 30:20.853
I have an evil twin.

30:20.887 --> 30:22.254
Swear to God,
we barely even talk.

30:22.288 --> 30:24.323
We have surveillance footage
of your vehicle.

30:24.356 --> 30:26.258
That's not even my car.
It's registered to you.

30:26.292 --> 30:28.327
Someone stole it.
We found the body
in your freezer.

30:28.360 --> 30:29.361
I have an evil twin.

30:29.395 --> 30:31.363
You tried that one
already.

30:31.397 --> 30:34.200
[ Sighs ] Oh, damnit.

30:34.233 --> 30:36.402
Those improv classes were
a total waste of money.

30:39.038 --> 30:41.707
Interviewer: Why were you so
confident about Jake Alpert?

30:41.740 --> 30:44.877
Well, Jake Alpert had clear
motive to kill Dante Smith.

30:44.911 --> 30:47.346
Jealousy because he was now
dating Layla Laughlin,

30:47.379 --> 30:50.549
who dumped him.
Yeah. And stealing the body
shows consciousness of guilt.

30:50.582 --> 30:53.319
But for a slam dunk, we needed
to tie him to the murder

30:53.352 --> 30:54.853
with physical evidence.

30:54.887 --> 30:57.023
And we were most definitely able
to do that.

30:57.056 --> 31:00.993
So, once we processed him,
we found traces of Dante's DNA.

31:01.027 --> 31:03.262
Isn't that to be expected
since he moved the body?

31:03.295 --> 31:04.730
Oh, DNA, yes.

31:04.763 --> 31:06.732
But he actually had
Dante's blood on him.

31:06.765 --> 31:08.901
But Dante had been
completely drained of blood

31:08.935 --> 31:10.136
before he was buried.

31:10.169 --> 31:12.871
Exactly.
So, here's the thing --

31:12.905 --> 31:16.075
we didn't just find Dante's
blood under his fingernails,

31:16.108 --> 31:18.644
which is where most murderers
get caught.

31:18.677 --> 31:22.714
We found traces of his blood
all over his hands and his arms

31:22.748 --> 31:25.417
and his face
and his chest.

31:25.451 --> 31:26.652
What,
did he bathe in it?

31:26.685 --> 31:27.920
[ Chuckling ] No.

31:27.954 --> 31:30.789
It's even weirder,
actually.

31:30.822 --> 31:32.258
Dante's blood
had been infused

31:32.291 --> 31:34.626
in his anti-aging
cosmetic cream.

31:34.660 --> 31:37.796
[ Dramatic music plays ]

31:37.829 --> 31:39.131
Carter: Jake!

31:39.165 --> 31:40.432
**

31:40.466 --> 31:42.134
Layla Laughlin's
number-one-selling

31:42.168 --> 31:45.537
anti-aging cosmetic cream,
de León,

31:45.571 --> 31:49.541
was made of human blood --
our victim's blood.

31:49.575 --> 31:53.812
I mean, I admire the woman
and all, but damn.

31:53.845 --> 31:55.114
That's just...

31:55.147 --> 31:56.915
Gross.
...nasty.

32:00.119 --> 32:02.121
Interviewer: In all your years
at the Bureau,

32:02.154 --> 32:03.122
have you ever seen anything
like this?

32:03.155 --> 32:04.556
Well, let me think.
I don't know.

32:04.590 --> 32:06.658
Uh, have I ever worked a case
where someone completely drained

32:06.692 --> 32:09.761
the victim of their blood,
only to use it as an ingredient

32:09.795 --> 32:12.664
in an anti-aging
cosmetic cream?

32:15.067 --> 32:16.902
What do you think?

32:16.935 --> 32:18.870
Well, Elizabeth Bathory --
she was the first

32:18.904 --> 32:20.939
female serial killer
in history.

32:20.973 --> 32:24.376
The phrase "bathed in blood"
originated with her...
Mm.

32:24.410 --> 32:27.846
...because, supposedly,
she would drain her victims

32:27.879 --> 32:29.515
and then washed herself
in their blood.

32:29.548 --> 32:32.484
Wow.
Now, Elizabeth Bathory...

32:32.518 --> 32:34.620
she had nothing
on Layla Laughlin.

32:34.653 --> 32:36.855
And Layla got rich
while doing it.

32:36.888 --> 32:38.257
De León Miracle Cream

32:38.290 --> 32:40.859
grossed over $200 million
last year alone.

32:40.892 --> 32:43.862
It's the signature product
in Untold Cosmetics.

32:43.895 --> 32:45.264
Interviewer: Did you have
any theories at the time

32:45.297 --> 32:47.133
as to why Layla targeted
her own boyfriend?

32:47.166 --> 32:50.669
Uh, yes. It's because Dante
had an exceptionally rare

32:50.702 --> 32:52.804
blood type -- Rhnull.

32:52.838 --> 32:54.040
And what's that?

32:54.073 --> 32:57.109
Rhnull is known as,
uh, "Golden Blood."

32:57.143 --> 32:58.610
You know,
it's the rarest blood type.

32:58.644 --> 33:01.113
Only 40 people
on the entire planet have it.

33:01.147 --> 33:03.215
Well, make it 39 now.

33:03.249 --> 33:04.883
Right. Yeah. So...

33:04.916 --> 33:07.019
Anyway, most people have eight
common blood types --

33:07.053 --> 33:08.687
you know, O positive,
O negative,

33:08.720 --> 33:10.456
A positive, et cetera.

33:10.489 --> 33:12.358
But what most people don't know
is that there's actually,

33:12.391 --> 33:14.293
you know,
millions of blood types,

33:14.326 --> 33:16.895
determined by the presence
or absence of certain antigens.

33:16.928 --> 33:19.165
But there's also a protein
called the Rh factor,

33:19.198 --> 33:21.200
which determines if your blood
is -- is positive

33:21.233 --> 33:22.234
or -- or negative.

33:22.268 --> 33:23.935
Most people
have some Rh factor.

33:23.969 --> 33:27.706
But if you lack it entirely,
you're Rhnull.

33:27.739 --> 33:29.908
You're [snaps fingers]
golden.

33:30.976 --> 33:33.712
Damn. [ Chuckles ]
How did you know all that?

33:33.745 --> 33:35.081
"Vampire Cop," Season 4.

33:35.114 --> 33:36.748
Our Big Bad was --
was Golden Boy,

33:36.782 --> 33:38.784
the vamp who only fed
on Rhnull blood.

33:38.817 --> 33:43.055
He became invincible, killed my
character in the cliffhanger.

33:43.089 --> 33:45.691
I-I regenerated and came back
the next season, but...

33:45.724 --> 33:47.259
You said you watched
every episode.

33:47.293 --> 33:49.261
That was a whole --
That was a whole story line.

33:49.295 --> 33:51.863
Yep. I-I did.

33:51.897 --> 33:54.200
And you -- [ Chuckles ]

33:54.233 --> 33:56.435
You were so good
on that show.

33:56.468 --> 33:58.337
W-Wasn't he goo--
Have you ever seen it?

33:58.370 --> 34:01.340
So, we brought Ms. Laughlin in
for questioning.

34:01.373 --> 34:03.442
We found that your
de León Miracle Cream

34:03.475 --> 34:05.344
was infused
with Dante's blood.

34:05.377 --> 34:08.746
[ Laughing ]
T-That's insane.

34:08.780 --> 34:10.616
We agree.

34:10.649 --> 34:13.152
But Dante was never
really missing.

34:13.185 --> 34:15.521
You held him captive
for eight months,

34:15.554 --> 34:17.523
all for
his rare blood.

34:17.556 --> 34:18.924
What happened?
Went too far one day?

34:18.956 --> 34:20.092
Took too much blood?

34:20.126 --> 34:23.061
Did Dante go into shock
or just die of blood loss?

34:23.094 --> 34:25.630
And then you buried him
in a shallow grave,

34:25.664 --> 34:27.766
thinking nobody
would ever find him.

34:27.799 --> 34:29.835
But what you didn't count on
was the mudslide

34:29.868 --> 34:32.371
that caused Dante's body
to resurface.

34:33.472 --> 34:35.407
[ Stammers, sighs ]

34:35.440 --> 34:40.346
You think that I killed Dante
for his blood?

34:40.379 --> 34:42.848
We tracked
a $50,000 payment

34:42.880 --> 34:44.449
from your company
to Jake Alpert.

34:44.483 --> 34:47.119
Sounds to us that you hired him
to steal the body back

34:47.152 --> 34:49.321
so the evidence against you
would never be discovered.

34:49.355 --> 34:54.092
I had nothing to do with Dante's
murder or -- or any of this.

34:54.126 --> 34:58.096
Ms. Laughlin,
I really looked up to you.

34:58.130 --> 35:00.499
Single mom like myself,

35:00.532 --> 35:03.569
getting her second act
at life.

35:03.602 --> 35:08.307
You taught me the key to success
was helping others.

35:08.340 --> 35:09.741
What happened
to that woman?

35:09.775 --> 35:12.511
You're staring her in the face
right now,

35:12.544 --> 35:16.982
and she is hoping that you're
good enough at your job

35:17.015 --> 35:19.385
to find Dante's real killer.

35:19.418 --> 35:24.055
Now, that's it for me.
I want my lawyer. Now.

35:24.089 --> 35:26.425
We obtained a search warrant
and raided the lab

35:26.458 --> 35:29.561
at Layla's company, looking for
proof of Dante's demise.

35:29.595 --> 35:32.130
However,
it was squeaky-clean.

35:32.164 --> 35:34.733
Layla's smart. Doing any sort
of experimental blood work

35:34.766 --> 35:38.170
in her place of business
would raise too many red flags

35:38.204 --> 35:39.705
and create
potential witnesses.

35:39.738 --> 35:42.073
So we got a warrant
for her residence.

35:42.107 --> 35:44.310
[ Dramatic music plays ]

35:44.343 --> 35:48.847
**

35:48.880 --> 35:51.383
Ma'am, we have a warrant
to search the premises.

35:51.417 --> 35:52.984
Is Ms. Laughlin here?

35:53.018 --> 35:54.220
They're fighting.

35:54.253 --> 35:55.487
Simone: Who is?

35:55.521 --> 35:56.822
Ms. Laughlin
and Chance.

35:56.855 --> 35:58.056
Interviewer:
Who was Chance?

35:58.089 --> 35:59.658
Chance was Layla's son.

35:59.691 --> 36:02.228
Brendon: The boy genius.
More of a con man
if you ask me.

36:02.261 --> 36:04.230
Talked his mother
into giving up control

36:04.263 --> 36:06.798
of her own company
so he could run it.

36:06.832 --> 36:08.467
[ Clattering ]

36:08.500 --> 36:09.735
Let us in.

36:09.768 --> 36:11.136
[ Gunshot ]

36:12.504 --> 36:14.740
So Layla's son was the one

36:14.773 --> 36:16.408
putting Dante's blood
in the cosmetic cream?

36:16.442 --> 36:17.443
Yeah.
That's right.

36:17.476 --> 36:19.211
And after Carter and I
interviewed her,

36:19.245 --> 36:20.446
Layla figured it out.

36:20.479 --> 36:22.614
But instead of telling us
that her son

36:22.648 --> 36:26.318
was the real-life vampire,
stealing that poor boy's blood,

36:26.352 --> 36:28.254
she confronted him
on her own.

36:28.287 --> 36:29.721
[ Whispers ]
Which was a bad idea.

36:29.755 --> 36:32.558
Yes, it was.
And by the time we got there,

36:32.591 --> 36:33.792
it was already too late.

36:33.825 --> 36:35.126
[ Gunshot ]

36:35.160 --> 36:37.263
[ Dramatic music plays ]

36:37.296 --> 36:39.231
Simone:
Stay right there.

36:39.265 --> 36:41.132
**

36:41.166 --> 36:42.534
FBI, drop it!

36:42.568 --> 36:43.769
Do it, now!

36:43.802 --> 36:45.036
Mom...?

36:45.070 --> 36:47.138
Chance!

36:47.172 --> 36:50.242
Put the gun down now.

36:50.276 --> 36:52.110
[ Breathing heavily ]

36:52.143 --> 36:54.613
I-I didn't mean
for any of this to happen.

36:54.646 --> 36:56.482
I just...

36:56.515 --> 36:57.916
She's gonna be okay,
right?

36:57.949 --> 36:59.318
[ Handcuffs clicking ]

36:59.351 --> 37:00.586
Right?

37:00.619 --> 37:04.423
**

37:07.626 --> 37:09.828
Shock waves rippled
around the world

37:09.861 --> 37:12.163
as cosmetics mogul
Layla Laughlin was shot

37:12.197 --> 37:14.833
and killed in her Bel Air home
earlier today.

37:14.866 --> 37:17.102
The alleged shooter, her son,
Chance Laughlin,

37:17.135 --> 37:19.971
was arrested by FBI agents
at the scene.

37:20.005 --> 37:23.375
In related news, Laughlin's
new "miracle" cream, de Léon,

37:23.409 --> 37:25.544
is being recalled
after it was determined

37:25.577 --> 37:27.012
that the secret ingredient

37:27.045 --> 37:28.647
that promised
the "fountain of youth"

37:28.680 --> 37:31.049
was, in fact, human blood.

37:31.082 --> 37:33.919
Interviewer:
Where did this blood-infused
cream idea come from?

37:33.952 --> 37:37.055
After we arrested Chance,
we learned that once he took

37:37.088 --> 37:39.190
the reins from his mother,
he became the company's

37:39.224 --> 37:41.727
head scientist in charge
of research and development.

37:41.760 --> 37:45.931
And in an effort to boost sales,
he created the de Léon cream

37:45.964 --> 37:47.433
using Dante's
golden blood.

37:47.466 --> 37:50.436
And at that point, well,
Layla was just a figurehead.

37:50.469 --> 37:52.971
She had no knowledge
of her son's misdeeds.

37:53.004 --> 37:55.974
Chance had sunk, you know,
millions into R&D,

37:56.007 --> 37:58.477
trying to isolate
the anti-aging antigens from --

37:58.510 --> 38:00.178
from normal human blood.

38:00.211 --> 38:03.181
And then when Dante
walked into his life

38:03.214 --> 38:04.783
with his golden blood...

38:04.816 --> 38:07.453
[ Sighs ]
Like a gift from above.

38:07.486 --> 38:08.920
Who was banging his mom.

38:11.590 --> 38:14.092
So, you had no ill will
towards Dante?

38:14.125 --> 38:18.229
No, no, not when I found out
he has Golden Blood.

38:18.263 --> 38:21.232
He was one of six people
with Rhnull blood

38:21.266 --> 38:23.134
in the whole country.

38:23.168 --> 38:25.604
Hospitals all around the world
would call on him to donate.

38:25.637 --> 38:28.440
Chance knew Dante
would never agree to donate

38:28.474 --> 38:30.008
for cosmetics, so...

38:30.041 --> 38:32.344
He abducted him
and held him prisoner.

38:32.378 --> 38:35.414
Chance fed him nourishing food
and kept him well-rested.

38:35.447 --> 38:38.917
In order to keep Dante and, most
importantly, his blood healthy.

38:38.950 --> 38:41.353
Interviewer:
But Dante's blood was basically
a renewable resource.

38:41.387 --> 38:42.554
Why kill him?

38:42.588 --> 38:46.124
I'd have kept him locked away
indefinitely.

38:46.157 --> 38:47.626
Would you now?

38:49.495 --> 38:50.896
Let's move on.
Mm-hmm.

38:50.929 --> 38:52.664
So what went wrong?
Why did Chance kill him?

38:52.698 --> 38:54.433
It was an accident.

38:54.466 --> 38:56.768
The demand for the de Léon cream
skyrocketed.

38:56.802 --> 38:58.937
And one day Chance took
too much blood,

38:58.970 --> 39:00.872
and Dante had a heart attack
and died.

39:00.906 --> 39:03.174
So you drained him
of every last drop.

39:03.208 --> 39:06.978
I even had to punch holes
in his neck to suck out

39:07.012 --> 39:09.581
